[3] Russia (Moscow)
Date: 18 Jul 2015
Source: uvao.mos.ru accessed 13 Jul 7 2015 [machine translation, abridged and edited]
http://uvao.mos.ru/presscenter/news/detail/2003596.html


Despite a decline in measles cases in the first half of 2015, the epidemic situation in the whole of the Moscow District remains dire. Specialists say that this year the District recorded 15 cases of the disease, compared within 37 cases in the District in 2014.

Rospotrebnadzor [the Health and Welfare Organisation] warned that the spread of measles is due to the infection of unvaccinated children or unvaccinated adults who remain susceptible to the disease. Also vulnerable are children of the 1st year of life, born to unvaccinated mothers. Also vulnerable are are organised groups of adults living in dormitories. At risk of measles include organized groups and persons living in the dorms, especially visitors from abroad who may have not been vaccinated. Previously in early June 2015 a family of 4 contracted measles within a 4-day period. The family comprised 2 adults and 2 children. The source of infection was 1 of the children who had not been vaccinated due to an oversight by the mother.

Vaccination in Russia carried out in accordance with the national calendar of preventive vaccinations. According to epidemic indications, vaccination is required for all contacts with persons with measles symptoms or those who had received only a single vaccination. Measles vaccine is available in sufficient quantities in all Health Department Clinics in Moscow.

