[4] Russia (Primorye
Date: 23 Jul 2015
Source: "NEWS: PRIMORYE" [machine translation, abbreviated and edited]
http://vestiprim.ru/2015/07/19/gostyam-i-zhitelyam-primorya-ugrozhaet-opasnoe-zabole


In recent years, measles cases have been imported from foreign countries (1 from Thailand, 1 from Hong Kong and 1 from South Korea), as well as a single case imported from the city of Moscow. In 2014 imported cases of measles came from the Philippines and Hong Kong, followed by the spread of infections among residents of Ussuriysk. In contrast during 2015, no cases of measles were recorded throughout the Primorsky Territory.

Measles is highly contagious infectious disease-producing pathogen transmitted from a sick person to a susceptible individual (without a history of measles and are not vaccinated against measles) through the air (talking, coughing, sneezing, etc.). Measles virus is volatile and and can remain infectious for some time in discharged mucus. Clinical manifestations of measles in the typical course of the disease is marked by cough, runny nose, conjunctivitis, general intoxication, temperature 38 deg C and above, stepwise maculo-papular rashes with 4-5th day of illness (day 1 - the face, neck, 2nd day - the body; day 3 - legs, arms) and pigmentation [rash].

The source of an outbreak is usually a sick person who is in the incubation period of the disease (for 8-10 days before the onset of symptoms) and up to the end of this period until the rash ends. So with measles cases (suspected cases) the sick person should be isolated from others, without a history of measles and previously or not immunized against this infection (found in an infectious diseases hospital or in the community), which will not disappear until the last elements of the rash finally recede. A recovered patient should not return to work until all symptoms have disappeared.

The main preventive measure at the present stage of measles is vaccination, which is held in the Russian Federation in accordance with the national calendar of preventive vaccinations in children 1 year and 6 years and adolescents aged 15-17 years and adults aged up to 35 years (inclusive), if they have not had measles or been vaccinated against the infection, or they have no information about prior vaccination against measles.

Particular attention is given to measles immunization among people of "risk groups", which include students of higher and secondary educational institutions, recruits, medical workers, employees of educational institutions, trade, transport, as well as citizens belonging to migrant workers, refugees and displaced people, nomadic groups, members of religious communities.

